<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Alright... this is an info post for all who care to read this forum, especially for newbies (no chars over 35 or 40)<p>

The first thing I learned is that it takes an experienced player to fully understand the power of a bard.  I have been playing the game for over a year (since Sept 99).  I recently started a bard to try it out.  Once I hit 26 and got my fear song, leveling is as easy as it was at level 4.  One might argue that a weekness of a bard is low ac and/or hitpoints... but what does it matter if the mob can't hit you?  Twisting fear/snare against any melee mob, with room to work with, is VERY easy and rich in exp.  No need for casters... you can solo or find a friend or friends that are melee classes and go to work.  Low strength?  So it takes a bit longer to kill them... if you find it takes too long for your liking, find a friend (must admit, double attack would be nice, but we can't have EVERYTHING).<p>

No mana = No medding.  Anyone experienced in playing a caster class for a while (again, at LEAST lev 35) understands this concept very well.<p>

Regen.  Well, that's an understatement.  At lev 30, playing a lute while healing lends you 15hp/tick.  Enough said.  I have had to learn to smoke MUCH faster to keep up with my bard healing himself (even when down to 1/2 bub).<p>

Resists.  I read most of the posts, and one experienced player noted that bard resistance songs are vital at higher levels.  This is absolutely true, and yet again, if you haven't played a char into the 40's, you simply could not understand.<p>

Charm.  This is fun, though not needed (in my experience).  I know bards that live by this to solo.  I still prefer fear/snaring those low-mid blues to yield 2 bubs an hour (in the 30's).  However, once you get up there, I'm sure it will take far too long to kill a mob melee with fear/snare, so I'm sure I'll get used to charming more.<p>

Did I mention heal?  Heal after fights, during fights, people beg for heals...  If you asked a couple of the warriors that I've partnered with lately, well, 'nough said.<p>

Mana regen.  Guaranteed group anywhere.  Bards are like clerics in that respect... they rarely get rejected.  Take a second and think of how many caster types are out there (those super cool wizzies and druids)... all starving for mana.<p>

Who needs weapons?  At higher levels, many situations call for a bard to become a caster of sorts... dmg/buffing/debuffing/healing with instruments only.  Very effective, and not always understood.  I started messing with this style of play soloing at 18 with DDD/chords/heal... lots of fun (especially the look of watchers who can't figure out where your weapons are).<p>

To sum up, bards can really do it all.  If you're in the mood to solo, then solo.... want company?  Join any group.  I have been tempted to challenge necros and druids to solo'ing duels... the most exp wins.  I get EXTREMELY fast exp in the open plains of Kunark.  Any class loves to find a bard partner... we can heal, mana regen, snare, fear, charm, dmg shield, endur breath, etc. etc... come on now.  Oh, I haven't even mentioned Selo's.  I have a high level ranger and shaman and can tell you how vital sow is.  I was in tears when I finally got sow at 39 with my ranger and I sell more sow potions with my sham then i can keep in inventory.  But ya know what?  When I log either of them on now, I feel like I'm crawling compared to my bard.  Especially in situations where you have to flee... with my bard I can be at a sliver of health and toss in my drum and safely zone.  Even with sow, if you're low enough health, you're dead.  If it wasn't for boats, I would never care about porting around (but after a year of EQ, I HATE boats- gladly paying 30pp per port).<p>

All this said, there are newbie bards out there that don't understand the class.  All classes can be very powerful when the player knows how to use their character well.  For example... there are warriors out there that don't taunt and shamen that think they are nukers.  These players do not have much experience, but everyone learns how to utilize their talents eventually.  I have yet to find a bard to partner with... but 2 bards have GOT to be an ABSOLUTE BLAST!!!<p>

hehehe... oh     TRACK RULES!!!</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
